	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>The future of the tuna industry in the Pacific</h1>

			
			<h4>
												22 February 2008
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> In December 2007, the director of the Western and Central Pacific Fisheries Commission (WCPFC) aired his views on issues facing the development of the tuna-fishing industry in the Pacific. From his perspective, ‘there are mounting pressures for the distant-water fishing nations to change traditional ways of operating ... from a system with minimal engagement or investment in shore-based services in the region, to one where local investment is probably going to determine access to long-term fishing opportunities'. But an over-arching concern remains the state of regional tuna stocks. ‘It is not much use promoting development, securing major investment, which most tuna-fishery development initiatives require, and find that tuna stocks become over-exploited and so jeopardise those investments’. The indications in 2007 are that fishing effort in the purse-seine fishery is expanding, and the director of the WCPFC notes that ‘industry pressure is being applied in management organisations like the WCPFC to take decisions that don’t limit catch or fishing effort when over-fishing is obviously occurring.’ </p><p> He also feels that IUU fishing is increasing in the region: ‘This not only involves fishing by fleets which do not participate in the work of the Commission but no doubt includes the activities of some vessels that belong to members of the Commission - particularly in respect of, for example, the under-reporting of catches. In addition, ‘the licensing of some of these vessels by any FFA member is in contravention of agreements both within the FFA (which relates to the licensing of vessels that are not on FFA’s regional register of foreign fishing vessels) and within the Commission ... this creates some major challenges for this organisation.’ </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>ATUNA</i>, December 2007</p><p>

<a href="http://www.atuned.biz/public/ViewArticle.asp?ID=4961" target="_self">http://www.atuned.biz/public/ViewArticle.asp?ID=4961</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> In theory, linking shore-based investment to access to fishing grounds may be interesting. But this presupposes that public infrastructure, available markets, etc, can ensure the economic profitability of the operation. Above all, and as highlighted in this interview, the main objective should be to conserve regional tuna stocks, as the basis for such investment, and the licensing policy of FFA members should take greater account of the regional recommendations and available information on the licenses as shared with other members. Existing FPAs with some FFA members have a role to play in achieving this.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

